category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to prevent a user from typing more than a fixed number of characters into a field. You may want to use this in any situation where you want to limit what the user can type, e.g. in a password field or during data entry.</p>
discussion=<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent whenever a character key is pressed. If the blinking text cursor is in a field, the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent to that field. When the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent to the field, it triggers this handler.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The Revolution engine must receive the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message in order to respond to a typed character (or in other words, the entry of a character is triggered by the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message), so trapping the message and not passing it prevents typing from being entered in the field.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>When the user types a key, the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> handler checks to see whether the field already contains the maximum number of characters allowed. The keyword <font face="Courier" size="11">me</font> refers to the object whose script contains the handler that is executing. In this case, <font face="Courier" size="11">me</font> refers to the field, because the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> handler is in the field's script. When a field is referenced in this way, Revolution returns the contents of the field. The length of that content is the number of characters it contains. So the expression <font face="Courier" size="11">the length of me</font> is the number of characters in the field.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If the field already contains the maximum number of characters, the handler beeps and doesn't <font face="Courier" size="11">pass</font> the keyDown message on, which causes the key press to be <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>lost</i></font>. If the field does not yet contain the maximum number of characters, the handler uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">pass</font> control structure to allow the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message to proceed along the message path, which causes the character to be added to the field normally.  For more details on the message path, see the section The <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Message Path</i></font> in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Note:</b></font>  The <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent for character keys, but not for non-character keys such as the arrow keys. If you want to trap such keys, or trap paste events, you'll need to use a <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> handler instead. However, for simple data entry fields, a <font face="Courier" size="11">rawKeyDown</font> handler is a little more complicated to implement and is usually overkill.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Limiting the number of characters during data entry
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> keyDown theKey</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> the <font color="#F88017">length</font> of <font color="#F88017">me</font> &gt;= 5 <font color="#980517">then</font> <font color="#0000FF">beep</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">else</font> <font color="#0000FF">pass</font> keyDown</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> keyDown</p>
title=Limiting the number of characters during data entry